You should not be using code like this to try and determine how long code takes to run. It&#39;s non-sensical because incrementing the count in an array is not tied to time or any unit of measurement. Instead, there are APIs which can be used to evaluate performance, such as [`console.time()`][1]:

        onmessage = function(buffer) {
          console.time(&#39;TimeSpentInWorker&#39;);

          // Your code...

          console.timeEnd(&#39;TimeSpentInWorker&#39;);
        };


You could also compare the difference between calling [`Date.now()`][2] twice or look into the [Performance API][3].


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Console/time
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date/now
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Performance

